    "solution": "**P1.A — schedule.** Dependence chain: `$F2`/`$F4` loads → `FADD $F4,$F2,$F4` → `FADD $F6,$F4,$F6` → `SD $F6`. All MEM and FP-SUM latencies = 3 (result usable at issue + latency):\n\n| Time | ALU 1cc | MU 3cc | MU 3cc | FPU + 3cc | FPU * 5cc |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 |  | LD `$F2` | LD `$F4` |  |  |\n| 2 |  | LD `$F6` |  |  |  |\n| 3 |  |  |  |  |  |\n| 4 |  |  |  | FADD `$F4`,`$F2`,`$F4` |  |\n| 5 |  |  |  |  |  |\n| 6 |  |  |  |  |  |\n| 7 |  |  |  | FADD `$F6`,`$F4`,`$F6` |  |\n| 8 |  |  |  |  |  |\n| 9 |  |  |  |  |  |\n| 10 | ADDUI `$R1` | SD `$F6` |  |  |  |\n| 11 | BNE `$R1`,`$R2` |  |  |  |  |\n\n`LD $F2`@1 and `LD $F4`@1 → ready @4, so the first `FADD`@4; its result (`$F4`) ready @7, so the second `FADD`@7 (there is only **one** FP-SUM unit, so the two FADDs must occupy different cycles anyway); `$F6` ready @10, so `SD`@10. `ADDUI` is placed at cycle 10 (with the store) because the loads **and the store** read `$R1` as their base — moving the index update earlier would corrupt the store address (WAR/anti-dependence on `$R1`). `BNE` needs the new `$R1` (1cc) → cycle 11; the instruction in the branch delay slot follows. No operation uses the FP-MUL in this loop.\n\n**P1.B — FLOPs/CC.** 2 floating-point ops (the two FADDs) over an 11-cycle iteration → **2/11 ≈ 0.18 FLOPs/CC**. The critical path is the LD → FADD → FADD → SD chain.\n\n**P1.C — unroll ×2 + a SUM-capable multiplier.** Unrolling by 2 doubles the work (two copies of the body, 4 FADDs) and exposes a **second, independent** dependence chain. Today the single FP-SUM unit is the bottleneck (it serialises I3 and I4). If the FP-MUL can also perform SUM at 3cc, the two iterations' FADDs can run on **two** SUM-capable units in parallel, and the loop overhead (ADDUI/BNE) is amortised over two iterations. Net: the chains overlap, FP-unit utilisation roughly doubles, and FLOPs/CC rises markedly (≈4 FP ops over ~13 cycles ≈ 0.3 vs 0.18) — throughput improves even though single-chain latency is unchanged.",
