    "solution": "**A. True (RAW) dependences** (read-after-write on a register), and only them:\n- `$f1`: I1→I3\n- `$f0`: I2→I3\n- `$f1`: I4→I5;  `$f0`: I3→I5\n- `$f0`: I5→I6 (store reads the sum)\n- `$f1`: I7→I9;  `$f0`: I8→I9\n- `$f1`: I10→I11;  `$f0`: I9→I11\n- `$f0`: I11→I12 (store)\n- `$2`: I13→I14;  `$2`: I14→I15 (store)\n\nAll the other `$f0`/`$f1` reuses are **WAW/WAR (name) dependences**, which Tomasulo removes through register renaming (reservation-station tags) — that is why, e.g., I4 (`ld $f1`) can issue and run before I3 has finished using the old `$f1`.\n\n**B. Yes — a configuration exists.** Read the per-instruction latency (START EXE → WB, no +1 in Tomasulo) from the table:\n- **Load unit = 2cc** — I1: 4−2=2, I2: 5−3=2, I7: 10−8=2, …\n- **FP multiplier = 10cc** — I3: 16−6=10, I9: 22−12=10\n- **FP adder = 3cc** — I5: 20−17=3, I11: 26−23=3\n- **Integer ALU = 1cc** — I14: 18−17=1; loads/stores for `$2` use the load/store path (I13 14→16 = 2cc).\n\nThe observed stalls are exactly what these latencies imply with enough RSs that issue is **never** RS-blocked (issue is in-order, 1/cc, with no gaps: I1…I15 issue at 1…15). I5's START EXE = 17 is `max(operand-ready, FU-free)+1`: its `$f0` operand comes from I3 whose WB is 16, so 16+1 = 17. ✔ I6's START = 21 = I5.WB(20)+1. ✔ I9 START = 12 needs the multiplier free after I3 (I3 occupies the MUL 6→16) and its operands (I7 WB 10, I8 WB 11) ready → 11+1 = 12. ✔ I11 START = 23 = I9.WB(22)+1. ✔ A single shared CDB suffices (no two WBs collide in one cycle). \n\n**C. Configuration that respects the execution** (not unique):\n- **2 Load/Store units, latency 2cc**, with e.g. 3 load RSs (back-to-back loads I1,I2,I4,I7,I8,I10 + I13/I15 never block issue).\n- **1 FP multiplier, latency 10cc**, with ≥2 mul RSs.\n- **1 FP adder, latency 3cc**, with ≥2 add RSs.\n- **1 integer ALU, latency 1cc**, with ≥1 RS.\n- A single common data bus (CDB).\n\nMore (or more deeply buffered) units would also fit; the point is that the latencies above + in-order 1/cc issue + this much buffering reproduce every ISSUE/START/WB in the table.\n\n**D. CPI.** The program spans from the first ISSUE (cycle 1) to the last WB (I12, cycle 29): total = 29 − 1 + 1 = 29 cycles for 15 instructions. **CPI = 29 / 15 ≈ 1.93** (IPC ≈ 0.52). The two 10-cycle `mul.d`s dominate — each stalls its dependent `add.d`.",
