    "solution": "**Assumption (stated explicitly): write-through.** Memory is updated on *every* write, so the three \"memory up to date?\" columns are **always \"yes\"** in every row. Cache states still follow MESI: read miss → **S** if another cache holds the block, else **E**; write → the writer becomes the sole valid copy (**M**) and all other holders go **I**. Each cache holds only ONE block, so any new block access **evicts** the one it held.\n\nStarting state (row 1, after `Px read block 2` as given): `Px`=E(0), `Py`=S(2), `Pz`=S(2).\n\n- **(2) Pz write B2:** `Pz` becomes sole owner → M(2); `Py` (S2) → I. `Px` keeps E(0).\n- **(3) Px read B2:** `Px` evicts B0, loads B2; `Pz` M(2)→S(2); `Px`→S(2). `Py`=I.\n- **(4) Pz read B1:** `Pz` evicts B2, loads B1 (nobody else has it) → E(1). `Px` keeps its (now sole) B2 copy → S(2).\n- **(5) Py write B2:** write-allocate + write → `Py` M(2); `Px` (S2) → I. `Pz`=E(1).\n- **(6) Px read B2:** `Px` loads B2; `Py` M(2)→S(2); `Px`→S(2). `Pz`=E(1).\n- **(7) Py write B1:** `Py` evicts B2, allocates+writes B1 → M(1); `Pz` (E1) → I. `Px` still S(2) (sole B2 holder).\n- **(8) Pz read B0:** `Pz` loads B0 (nobody else has it) → E(0). `Px`=S(2), `Py`=M(1).\n- **(9) Px write B0:** `Px` evicts B2, write-allocates B0 → M(0); `Pz` (E0) → I. `Py`=M(1).\n- **(10) Py read B2:** `Py` evicts B1, loads B2 (nobody else has B2 now — `Px` evicted it) → E(2). `Px`=M(0), `Pz`=I.\n- **(11) Py read B2:** read **hit** on `Py`'s E(2) — no change.\n- **(12) Pz write B1:** `Pz` write-allocates B1 (nobody else has it) → M(1). `Px`=M(0), `Py`=E(2).\n- **(13) Px read B1:** `Px` evicts B0, loads B1; `Pz` M(1)→S(1); `Px`→S(1). `Py`=E(2).\n- **(14) Pz read B0:** `Pz` evicts B1, loads B0 (nobody else has it) → E(0). `Px`→S(1) (now sole B1 holder). `Py`=E(2).\n- **(15) Pz read B1:** `Pz` evicts B0, loads B1; `Px` already S(1) → both S(1). `Py`=E(2).\n- **(16) Py read B1:** `Py` evicts B2, loads B1; all three now hold B1 → `Px`=`Py`=`Pz`=S(1).\n- **(17) Px write B1:** `Px` write → M(1); `Py`,`Pz` (both S1) → I.\n- **(18) Px read B1:** read **hit** on `Px`'s M(1) — no change.\n- **(19) Pz write B1:** `Pz` write-allocates B1 → M(1); `Px` (M1) → I. `Py`=I.\n\nUnder write-through, the writer pushes the new value to memory on each write, so there is no dirty/stale memory and no write-back traffic on eviction — memory stays current throughout. (M here means \"sole owner\", not \"memory stale\".)",
